    I might be persuaded into building one,  see the @{"card-ware" LINK Card_Ware_Node} status :^)

@ENDNODE


@NODE shell_usage_Node "NetProbe/Shell Version"

    Template:

    O=Owner/S,IP=IP-Addr/S,Kick=Kickstart/S,WB=Workbench/S,NIPC/S,
    FM=FastMem/S,CM=ChipMem/S,P=Processor/S,C=Chips/S,
    S=Services/S,E=Entities/S,A=All/S,
    SR=ScanRealms/S,SH=ScanHosts/S,SA=ScanAll/S,
    K=Kludge/S,MT=MaxTime/K/N,MP=MaxPackets/K/N,
    R=Realms/K/M/A,SF=SaveFile/K/A


    This is a version which can be used with automated shell scripts.
    It's also useful on machines not (yet) equipped with MUI.

    Feature ;-)  The shell version does not honor the preferences file
                 of the MUI version.

    O=Owner/S           see Lots of @{"Checkboxes and Strings" LINK Strings_Node}
    IP=IP-Addr/S
    Kick=Kickstart/S
    WB=Workbench/S
    NIPC/S
    FM=FastMem/S
    CM=ChipMem/S
    P=Processor/S
    C=Chips/S

    S=Services/S        see @{"Services" LINK Services_Node}
    E=Entities/S        see @{"Entities" LINK Entities_Node}

    A=All/S             All information possible

    SR=ScanRealms/S
    SH=ScanHosts/S
    SA=ScanAll/S

    K=Kludge/S          see @{"40.2-kludge" LINK Kludge_Node}
    MT=MaxTime/K/N      see @{"Preferences" LINK Preferences_Node }
    MP=MaxPackets/K/N
    SF=SaveFile/K/A

    R=Realms/M/A        List of Realms to scan


@ENDNODE


@NODE Realms_ListView_Node "NetProbe/ListView of Realms"

    In this ListView you'll see the realms in your network.  Double-click
    on one realm to scan it for information.  This is equal to selecting
    a realm and pressing the @{"Scan Hosts" LINK Scan_Hosts_Node} button.

    This button will be inactive if your network has no realm servers.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Hosts_ListView_Node "NetProbe/ListView of Hosts"

    The ListView displays the hosts of the last scanned realm,  or all
    hosts if there is no realm server.  Click a host to show detailed
    information.

@ENDNODE


@NODE  Entities_Node "NetProbe/ListView of Entities"

    In this ListView you'll see the Entities offered by the selected Host.

    The checkbox above the ListView enables or disables scanning for
    Entities.

@ENDNODE


@NODE  Services_Node "NetProbe/ListView of Services"

    In this ListView you'll see the services offered by the selected host.

    The checkbox above the ListView enables or disables scanning for
    Services.

    Nota bene:

    Reporting entities of remote hosts running nipc.library version 40.2
    or less is buggy.  See also the @{"40.2-kludge" LINK Kludge_Node} and the @{"Preferences" LINK Preferences_Node}.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Scan_Realms_Node "NetProbe/Scan Realms"

    This button scans the network for realms. It will be inactive if your
    network has no realm servers.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Scan_Hosts_Node "NetProbe/Scan Hosts"

    Scans the network or a selected realm for its hosts and retrieves
    information selected with the @{"Check Boxes" LINK Strings_Node}.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Scan_All_Node "NetProbe/Scan All"

    This button will be inactivate if your network has no realm servers.

    It performs mainly a @{"Scan Realms" LINK Scan_Realms_Node} followed by a @{"Scan Hosts" LINK Scan_Hosts_Node} for each Realm.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Scan_Ping_Node "NetProbe/Scan Ping"

    This button scans one single host in your realm.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Quit_Node "NetProbe/Quit"

    Obvious, isn't it?

@ENDNODE


@NODE Strings_Node "NetProbe/Checkboxes and Strings"

    In this area,  you'll find checkboxes for different scan parameters
    and the results of a scan run.  There are following options:


    Owner               The name of the owner.

    IP-Address          The IP-Address of the hosts.  This information
                        may not be available in further releases of Envoy.

    Kickstart           The Kickstart version of the host.

    Workbench           The Workbench version of the host.

    NIPC Version        The version of the nipc.library in the host.

    Fast Memory         The amount of fast memory installed in the host.

    Chip Memory         The amount of chip memory installed in the host.

    Processor           The processor and FPU of the host.

    Chips               The custom chips in the host.


@ENDNODE


@NODE About_Node "NetProbe/About"

    This simply shows a little requester.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Save_List_Node "NetProbe/Save List"

    This saves the scanned list to the file selected in the preferences
    window.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Preferences_Node "NetProbe/Preferences"

    This shows the preferences window.

    Here you set

        - maximum scan time per inquiry (in seconds).

        - maximum number of packets accepted.

        - path for the @{"Save List" LINK Save_List_Node} option.

        - @{"40.2-kludge" LINK Kludge_Node}.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Kludge_Node "NetProbe/40.2-kludge"

    Nipc.library 40.2 or older returned random garbage when inquiried
    about services.  This in turn pretty much messed up my Envoy core 
    functions.

    Technically speaking, this happens when performing a NIPCInquiry with
    the QUERY_SERVICE flag set. Luckily only alphanumerical data is
    garbled.

    If you have a machine in your network with an antique Envoy installation,
    you can instruct the core functions to discard all information received
    from those machines with old libraries.

@ENDNODE
